Spectacular jump in "wingsuit" over Bogota
Sportsman Jhonathan Florez jumped Thursday from a helicopter over Bogota, the Colombian capital.
Equipped with a wingsuit (a combination with wings), it went up to 160 km/h above the famous Monserrate sanctuary, located at more than 3,000 meters above sea level, where many bastards had gathered to observe its exploit.
A black box in your car?
While planners in the U.S. road network find it difficult to find the money to repair the decaying highway infrastructure, many are looking for a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches itself to the dashboard of your car.
The aircraft, which record all the miles travelled by a motorist and transmit the information to officials, are at the centre of a controversial attempt in Washington and in the planning government offices to reshape the obsolete system of financing the main U.S. roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axis planning suddenly sparked a lively debate and turbulent alliances.
The libertarians have joined environmental groups to pressure the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you are travelling on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is appalled.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress cannot agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay according to the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already embarked these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS surveillance system, for an experimental trip.
This is truly indispensable for our nation.
"It's not like we have a choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, General Manager of the Southern California Association of Governments, who predicts that the state will begin recording the miles travelled by each Californian motorist by 2025.
There's going to be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, financed with taxes paid by the Americans at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars can travel more than miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gas tax is simply not tenable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
"This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative," he said.
Wonks calls this from user fees to mileage.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state's ambitious laws on global warming.
But representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Chair of the House of Representatives Transport Committee, said he also considered it the most viable long-term alternative.
Supporters of the Reason Foundation's free market also appreciate the idea of charging drivers per mile.
"It's not just a tax in a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, Vice President of Politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move towards payment by mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved approximately 10,000 cars.
But the Speaker of the House killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several States and major cities are making progress.
The most determined is Oregon, which mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's largest experience.
These motorists will soon pay the Crown kilometric fees instead of gas taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And coalition I-95, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the American east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their cars with a device, drivers were worried that the government could follow their every move.
"A concern about Big Brother and that kind of thing is a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who leads strategic performance management in the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the start of the trial, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged localization devices."
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily goings and comings.
Nevada is one of a few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car is travelling, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, added Khan, citizens will be more comfortable.
Researching this technology has led some state agencies to use a small start-up in California called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to assist motorists who pay taxes to states.
She was looking to break into the emerging auto insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices it tests have pleased the planners of the major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't record their speed and locate them," said Ryan Morrison, Executive Director of True Mileage.
Big mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much cheaper ways and far less intrusive methods of doing so.
In Oregon, planners try the experiment by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles travelled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are seeking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide "driving payment" insurance, and create a real-time speed dataset from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Car drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers to them," said a document on urban development.
However, some transport planners are wondering whether the whole debate on mile payment is not just a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say that Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by increasing gas taxes.
A single or additional annual tax could be imposed on hybrid drivers and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
"It is not necessary to resort to radical surgery when we simply need aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, Director of Legislation and Public Affairs to the Commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: four new listeners
The English musician has not finished surprise this year.
Starting from The Next Day, released in January, he has concocted a luxury re-edition scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already emerged on the web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone panicked.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he said that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dates from 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that he could still be counted on to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one trick in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke has planned to reissue this album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, entitled The Next Day Extra, will be presented in the form of three discs: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four clips already unveiled.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe edition, five specially unveiled songs for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie also made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both each record, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and covers, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, above all, he gives a taste of his new Atomica title, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with very forward guitars and well-controlled rock electricity.
New ones already listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the Web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a light cavalcade that slows down gradually to give way to a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John's Rocket Man or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems in any case in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his strangeness: would it come from another planet?
The bewitching guitar riffs make you want to leave the Earth.
Bowie has fun playing the chameleon with these titles: alternately informant, man aboard a rocket, Martian potential...
He hides and reveals at once, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
It is not surprising that he has a mask in his hand in the photograph of the campaign L'Invitation au Voyage, of the Louis Vuitton brand, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that injured soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Mr. Nicholson assured that before their release, members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released until they are ready, he said.
Critics accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured military personnel - who do not meet the "universal service" rule of the army requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for pension benefits.
In particular, they cited two cases reported by La Presse Canadienne, including that of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist from London, Ontario, suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder, was released from the military despite his request to remain for another year in order to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case occurred after Corporal Glen Kirkland, who stated before a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed out before being ready because he did not meet the universality of service rule.
Mr. Hawkins pointed out that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultation sessions, but that it was totally different than wanting to leave.
"I told them I wasn't ready," he said in an interview with La Presse Canadienne on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was a way I could stay, and they said no.
Since the beginning of the major fighting in Afghanistan, the army has been struggling to determine what latitude it can give to wounded soldiers who want to remain in the ranks, but who are not fit for combat.
Under current rules, seriously injured soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for deployment abroad, they may be forced to leave the army.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicate that of the 1,218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the required length of service to obtain pension benefits.
Liberal veteran spokesman Jim Karygiannis asked Wednesday for Corporal Hawkins to be reinstated, while NDP Jack Harris called for an immediate end to "this shameful practice."
