Frontier Airlines plans to charge for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for passengers carrying carry-on baggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for carry-on baggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although in its announcement on Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them as the aircraft descends.
The new hand luggage charges are for bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free of charge.
Frontier stated that it would charge $25 if the charges were paid in advance and $100 if the travellers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Frontier's spokesperson, Kate O'Malley, indicated that the $100 was intended to encourage travellers to pay the fees in advance.
"We don't want to charge this price," she explained.
Airlines started charging for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these charges put as much as they could in hand baggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no longer room in these compartments.
These charges are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said these new fees will not really be used to raise money.
It is a question of making the most loyal Frontier customers understand that it becomes increasingly difficult to find room in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline's website will not have to pay.
For example, a passenger queued at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and registration procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of these charges before arriving at the door.
Frontier's carry-on baggage charges will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often blush about luggage and other expenses, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street consider the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines charge enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of loss.
However, many of them did not pay the cost of baggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. had applied the first carry-on baggage charges three years ago, and low-cost Allegiant followed a little later.
The only other company imposing such charges is the Hungarian company Wizz Air, said the consultant to airlines Jay Sorensen, who closely follows the charges in supplement.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated Spirit's carry-on baggage costs to be $50 million per year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently travelled on Spirit and wondered what he would find at the gate when passengers discovered the unusual carry-on baggage charges imposed by the company.
"I've never seen such a smooth boarding process in my entire professional career," he said.
I expected to see teeth gnashing and a fight at the door.
The aircraft was full, he added, "the passengers boarded at the speed of lightning."
Frontier also makes like Spirit and applies a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier indicated that passengers who take a soda or juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who take coffee can be tightened free of charge.
It will always distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for drinks in 2008 but went back seven months after passengers complained and no other major airline followed.
Frontier's decision to charge for carry-on baggage when passengers do not buy their tickets directly from the airline is his last attempt to encourage customers to go to his site.
Airlines pay online travel vendors like Orbitz $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This prompted all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of using an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it began offering only half a mile of loyalty to customers who bought their tickets via an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she reduced miles' bonuses by 25% on a trip.
For example, a 1,000-mile Frontier trip purchased from an online travel agency would save 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seat in advance only if they buy their ticket directly from Frontier's website.
Frontier has a loyal clientele in its home town, Denver, but its business is shrinking and it is losing money.
Revenues dropped by 9% and its flight capacity decreased by almost 13% in the first quarter, according to financial results released on Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to correct Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
NSA calls into question an "internal error" and not hackers for the breakdown of its site
The National Security Agency working in the shadows said on Friday that it was a bug that caused the breakdown of its public site for a few hours, not hackers as some claimed online.
"NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours this evening due to an internal error that occurred during a planned update," the spy agency said in an email statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
The allegations that the breakdown was due to a distributed denial of service attack [SDS] are false.
Earlier this evening, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still cannot access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesperson told ABC News that the agency's sensitive internal network was "not at all" compromised.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesperson explained.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the breakdown of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
Cyber-tactic is not very sophisticated and attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
The formerly ultra-secret NSA, a time known as the "No Such Agency", has been under the spotlight and has been heavily criticized in recent months as a result of a wave of revelations about its extensive national and foreign communications monitoring programs – which are part of the NSA's secret files stolen from the agency and disclosed by the former disillusioned NSA consultant, Edward Snowden.
This growing controversy around the agency has led to many speculations that tonight's incident was the result of a targeted cyber-operation.
Delta Downtown now closed
The Delta Centre-Ville hotel closed on Thursday in Montreal, after 36 years of existence.
The investment fund that owned the building sold it to developers who will turn it into student residences.
Three hundred and fifty people worked at the hotel.
Of these, 200 have still not found a new job.
Delta promises not to let down his employees.
Employers came to meet with employees directly on site, and employees were met individually to assess their needs.
"This support will continue for the next six months," explains Regional Director of Labour Relations at Delta Hotels, Félix Bisson.
The closure of the Delta is taking place in a highly competitive hotel market.
The investment fund that owned that building had choices to make.
Either he was reinvesting in the building to continue operating it, so there were investments of tens of millions while the competition is very fierce, there are many new hotels that appeared in Montreal.
"Or he was selling it to someone else and that's what happened," explains Paul Arsenault, Chair of Transat Tourism at the UQAM School of Management Sciences.
