Bombardier's profit declines, while aircraft deliveries and orders decline
Bombardier Inc., a Canadian aircraft and rail manufacturer, reported a 15% drop in its net profit on Thursday, under pressure from lower orders and deliveries of aircraft during the third quarter and contractual problems in its Trains division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, also did not provide in-flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft nor did it provide information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial commissioning schedule by September.
After the pilot's inaugural flight about a month and a half ago, the pilot flew only three times, and the question then arose as to whether the test phase was on track.
The results did not match the forecast and the share price fell by 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at the National Bank Financial, lowered his rating Thursday from "overperformance" to "sector performance" due to the low potential for the stock exchange to increase in the next quarter or two.
"Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are really disappointed with the profit margin in the Transportation division," Cameron Doerksen said in a memo to customers.
We expect Bombardier to register new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight test program moves forward.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more sceptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will be able to catapult it in the lower segment of a market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delay.
But the number of firm orders for CSeries aircraft has so far been modest at 177. It seems that potential buyers are waiting for the results of the flight tests to validate the company's assertions about the energy efficiency and savings potential of the new airliner.
At present, the company has registered a total of 403 orders and purchase commitments with 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and CEO, is confident that Bombardier will reach its target of 300 firm orders prior to the commercial launch of the first aircraft.
Leaders also reassured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was moving forward in accordance with the schedule.
"The test aircraft did not remain on the ground longer than expected," said Mr. Beaudoin at a conference call, adding that ground testing and software updates were planned during the aircraft's downtime.
Each manufacturer plans differently.
We decided to make a first flight and to schedule an update period, and that's what we did.
This will happen again throughout the flight program.
The second of the five test aircraft is expected to fly in the coming weeks, while the others will follow shortly thereafter, said the company.
Yet analysts are skeptical that the first customer can fly a CSeries aircraft only 12 months after its inaugural flight.
