George Kerevan: The Breakup of Europe Gives Scots a Choice · Global Voices
Another day, another worrying history of independence.
This time, we are being warned that an independent Scotland would be required to join the European free movement zone in order to be able to join the EU.
And now we hear stories of passport control in Berwick and a border of barbed wires along the Hadrian wall.
Although Strathclyde's newspaper pointed to the possible economic consequences of greater freedom of movement with the rest of Europe, this was not in the headlines (and it was to be expected).
Neither did anyone say that EU Member States spend much of their time circumventing their formal rules when it suits them.
Since Scotland is not part of the Schengen area at the moment, continued non-compliance with the rules would be a thin concession that Brussels could offer in return for everything it wants from Scots.
So it's a story that's not one.
And a story so old that it is now frozen: I heard for the first time the boobard that "independence means passport control" more than 40 years ago.
Yet one has forgotten an interesting point in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe's instructions, in fact?
Why exchange the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the major post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely at a standstill.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe officially died.
Throughout Europe, parties that oppose the EU or campaign for the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the alternative eurosceptic party for Germany, founded only this year and arrived from nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the September federal elections and released the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been a national opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has been a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the carcan burdening national economies through accession to the single currency, has led many people to believe that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments with excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Instead, the European system has put on its members favourable exchange rates for German exporters – something German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-à-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make dark cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper malaise linked to productivity in Europe.
Following the "green" energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidise French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer – the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a staggering cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
Not all wage freezes in the world will prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is rumbling, particularly in France, one of the leading leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite considered the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport for its political legitimacy and imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy struggling.
As a result, Marine Le Pen's far-right party, the National Anti-European Front, has just won a crucial by-election, sending the socialists back to power in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split of the right will automatically favour the left.
What does Marine Le Pen do with his new popularity with the French white working class?
It wants to use next year's European elections to create a single anti-currency and anti-European bloc in the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties are well represented in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-currency feeling unique in Europe will unite and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something that will look more like the free "Europe of Nations (sovereigns)" favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies could retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will look soft in the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of little England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending Berlin and Brussels for a walk.
I believe that Scotland could accommodate a freer European agreement if we kept our own motto.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should imitate Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – and it should be noted – the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, as it won a spectacular majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the dark cuts proposed (and implemented) by the Chancellor of the Labour Exchequer, Alistair Darling, and the subsequent Conservative/Liberal-Democrat coalition.
It would now be ridiculous for Scotland to vote for independence if it were to accept the austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Growing older earlier
Studies show that African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty age earlier than white girls.
Physical changes do not mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not as pronounced among boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Does a mother have to worry if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr.Paul Kaplowitz, pedo-endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new standard.
"I spend a lot of time reassurance to parents – in general, this does not indicate a rapid shift towards full puberty," Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as the budding of the breasts, hairs under the arms and in the pubic area and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of the first period in the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, compared to three quarters in 1970.
"Once the chest has begun to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first rules appear," said Kaplowitz, also the author of "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual appearance of puberty, but it is considered "early" when the development of the chest is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster evolution may justify tests performed by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumours or cysts.
Treatments are available to delay the onset of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormonal treatment are based on child age, development rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is careful with drugs but recognizes that "controlling puberty can alleviate certain behavioural problems and the feeling for girls to be different from others."
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young girls to have their period.
"They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will deal with hygiene issues," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at the age of 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about the rules, she wasn't emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories brought to the public's attention about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz states that the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 years who linked the percentage of fat to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty age earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have hair on their face and in the younger pubic area, the trend towards true early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians attending the PAA conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common, even in infants and toddlers.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the real appearance of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a child endocrinologist working at the Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to speak with their child.
"This may mean having a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will react well in general.
Girls whose puberty is early need to be reassured that, even when it happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
