Singapore’s pledge lenders take advantage of middle classes forced to tighten belt
Janani Amirthalinga deposits a bracelet, ring and pair of gold earrings at a pawnshop at Bendemeer Shopping Centre in Singapore to pay for her daughters' tuition fees.
"My husband and I just bought a house so all my money went into it," says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns $3,000 from Singapore ($2,400) per month as an administrator and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she says.
In fact, demand is such in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – that ValueMax, where it made its transaction, this week became the third pledge loan company to be introduced on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
To pledge jewelry is not only a quick way to get cash – $1,300 from Singapore in the case of Mrs.Amirthalinga – but it's almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
In general, Singapore pledge lenders charge an effective annual interest rate of 17%, just above the 15.4% offered by the United Overseas Bank, a local funder with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawn lenders have the advantage of not asking for credit checks or proof of salary, and can release loans faster than banks.
As a result, millions of people across the region are turning to pawn lenders as families feel the pressure of rising costs of living and the over-indebtedness of households and consumers.
After five years of solid growth since the global financial crisis, and low-cost credit fuelled by overly lax monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pledge lenders to make up for the difference as their economies slow down.
This week, the Standard & Poor's credit rating agency cited the growing household debt, mainly due to the rise in mortgage loans, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
She stated that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest debt-to-GDP ratio in Asia.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 per cent of GDP, compared to 60 per cent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which has just emerged this week from a technical recession.
On Thursday, data showed continued weakness in exports and a slowdown in consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that with rising costs, people in the middle or bottom [of the salary scale] are looking to supplement their income as they can," says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historically high gold prices over the past two years have made people quick to pledge their personal belongings to touch the cash value of their jewellery.
In Singapore, about 70 per cent of the pawnshops in the city-state's 200 pawnshops are in gold.
People say, "The price of gold is high, let's pledge Grandma's gold chain and we'll come back for it next month."
In Thailand, EasyMoney, the largest provider of pawnshops, has registered a 20 per cent increase in the number of customers using its shops in recent months.
The increase is such in the pledge lending sector that ValueMax, an operator of the Bendemeer boutique and 15 other boutiques like this one in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia – where it already has four boutiques – but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, its Managing Director.
The company will fund them using 60% of Singapore's $66 million raised this week when it was introduced on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some low-rate lenders have been criticized for the exorbitant interest rates they practice, Ms. Yeah indicates that pawning not only offers lower rates than other lenders, but also does not directly increase debt.
"Customers mortgage property they already own, and monetizing their personal property does not increase household debt," she says.
Pledging is becoming increasingly socially accepted as a means of obtaining guaranteed financing in the short term.
People who go to pawnshops are not only those who have financial problems.
The wealthy people of Singapore also go to the ValueMax pawnshops to pledge gold ingots or Rolex watches, which can account for up to 60% of their cash purchase price.
We see clients from all walks of life.
"They can be well-off people who need to borrow in the short term for business or investment, or small businesses that need cash to get through a difficult course," says Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
