FAA: Air passengers can now use gadgets on aircraft (but not make a call with their mobile phone)
Airline passengers will be able to use their door-to-door electronic devices to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music – but not talk on their mobile phones – under the highly anticipated new directives issued on Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, said FAA administrator Michael Huerta at a press conference.
Airlines will be required to demonstrate to the FAA that their aircraft are complying with the new guidelines and that they have updated crew member training manuals and aircraft storage rules to be in compliance.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue are among the companies that have already submitted plans.
"Based on the plan, we could approve an expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not supposed to turn them on until the aircraft reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives its green light.
Passengers are expected to turn off their aircraft when the aircraft descends before landing and not turn them on until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new directives, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during take-offs, landings and ground rolling, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Association of Professional Flight Waitants, said she was pleased with these changes.
"Once the new policy is implemented safely – and we will work closely with carriers for this – it will benefit everyone," Glading said in a statement.
We are frankly tired of feeling like "room supervisors" when it comes to this issue.
But it will always be forbidden to connect to the Internet to surf, exchange emails and SMS or download data below 10,000 feet, said the agency.
Passengers will have to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices in air mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the online Scrabble-style game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 when he was thrown out of an American Airlines plane after refusing to turn off his device while the aircraft was parked at the door.
And heavier devices like laptops will always have to be stored because they could hurt someone if they flew through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory authority for mobile phones rests with the Federal Communications Commission and not with the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national expert in transport safety on CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially create interference with navigational instruments, but because we know, according to FCC, that they could disrupt mobile phone relay antennas if they are used on board," said Rosenker.
An industry advisory committee established by the FAA to review the issue recommended last month that the government allow for wider use of personal electronic devices.
The pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to ease restrictions on its use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there are no valid security reasons for these prohibitions.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to apply as the use of devices has become pervasive.
Some studies indicate that at least one third of passengers forget to turn off their aircraft, or deliberately do so.
The FAA began limiting the use of electronic devices in 1996 as a result of reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers were carrying FM radios, the then high-tech gadget.
New airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand FAA-approved electronic interference.
Airlines have allowed their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruise altitudes for several years.
Aircraft modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are expected to allow wider use of electronic devices under the new directives, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit radio transmissions of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, only issue minimal transmissions when you turn a page.
But transmissions are stronger when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is one of those who are pressing for a relaxation of restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, the company's executives loaded a line plane of Kindle e-book readers and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This has led members of the FAA Advisory Committee to have mixed feelings about whether or not the use of the devices presents a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers stated that he believed the interference from the aircraft was real, although the risk was minimal.
Other committee members stated that there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that indicate that aircraft can interfere with aircraft systems, and that most of them are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA authorize pilots to ask passengers to turn off their aircraft during instrument landings under low visibility conditions.
A travel industry group welcomed the changes, calling for sensible arrangements for technology-equipped travellers.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not inconsistent with safety," said Roger Dow, President and Director of the U.S. Travel Association.
