Is the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of bringing companies together and defining what wealth and job creators want to see change in our relationship with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK entrepreneurs and asked them what they thought of Britain, business and the EU.
YouGov interviewed more than 1,000 entrepreneurs, who are broadly representative of all sizes of businesses, sectors and regions of Great Britain.
The findings of the investigation will be a surprise to many.
We have discovered that the vast majority of companies are now seeking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and developing while the EU states are stagnating.
They want the government to give priority to new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil rather than getting stuck in the long and arduous process of reforming Europe's institutional arcanes.
When asked for their views on specific policy issues – ranging from monopoly regulation to product laws – the majority of business leaders believe that control over these key competencies should go back to Westminster.
The single market has caused general dissatisfaction, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels Regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trading area – 40% of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Finally, and more importantly, our survey of business leaders revealed that a large majority wanted Britain to pursue initiatives to change the Treaty and develop a trade-based relationship with the EU rather than policy.
This conclusion, which can be found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the business world is insisting on a "significant change" that restores power to the UK.
