How biometrics will invade our lives
No more passwords to type to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French and Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy director general of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person making transactions in a universe as transverse and transnational as the Internet.
Organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this craze for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 alone and in France alone, the Commission nationale de l'informatique et des libertés has authorised 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the form of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everyone will soon be able to be identified anywhere and anytime," said Justin Brookman, consumer privacy manager at the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometry will be based on new techniques that will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work the concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, Technical Director of the domain of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - we cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted over the last twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the coloured part of the eye).
By increasing the accuracy of the sensors and the computing capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture's R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we're doing research on voice recognition or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, Intel Labs Security Research Director.
A unique and falsifiable marker, DNA is also a source of hope and concern.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective Studies at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the criminal investigation police a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is the one they claim to be).
Identification has so far been concerned with the issue of identity papers: biometrics (fingerprints, photographs, iris) must be compared with the information the State has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not attempt to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance to a hotel or store.
"We collect images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities who circulate freely on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, NEC France's manager of business development for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a picture of a quidam who queues in a store, track his progress through facial recognition and calculate wait time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening of a computer).
In addition, more recently, presence control has been introduced.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend who points for another," explains Cyrille Bataller of Accenture.
But, more and more, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by introducing their card and placing their hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the keystroke of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retail stores: when paying in-store with its credit card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the box 30 seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the manager of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, due to the lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts continue to be concerned.
"The progress of facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance," predicts Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada.
