The cardinals are the highest churchmen placed in the Catholic Church behind the pope, and those who elect him, so Francis will appoint his first group of men who will ultimately choose his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, as soon as a cardinal reaches the age of 80, he can no longer participate in the election of a pope – it is therefore a group of 120 "cardinal voters".
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said that a meeting bringing together all the existing cardinals would be held before the ceremony during which bishops would be raised to the dignity of cardinal, known as the Consistory.
"Pope Francis has decided to communicate his decision to convene the Consistory of February in advance in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings requiring the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world," Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of the Catholic Voices said that by February, the number of cardinal voters will likely have decreased.
He said that a pope usually appointed as many cardinals as necessary to ensure that the number of cardinal voters reached 120 and as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wanted.
Next year's consistory will be important because it will be the first since the election of Pope Francis in March of this year, said Valero.
At the moment, there is a kind of tendency to favour Europe and in particular Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new pope will name cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he added.
40% of Roman Catholics live in South America, but a small number of cardinals represent them.
Cardinals will also be the first to be chosen since Francis formed the council of cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from all over the world to examine ways of reforming the church.
Previously, the pope decided on his own.
"Now François has chosen these eight cardinals to help him," Valero explained.
He added that it was "very possible" for Francis to seek advice from the cardinals.
But we have never experienced such a situation – it is totally new.
Valero indicated that the popes generally raised bishops representing large communities to the rank of cardinal, but that Francis was "full of surprises – so we don't know who he will name".
GM recalls some of its new pickups in the United States to repair the seat back
General Motors Co recalls nearly 19,000 of its brand new Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra 2014 pickups to resolve a problem with manually tilting files, according to a statement by the U.S. vehicle safety regulator on Friday.
On some pickups, the front seats could have a defect in the tilt mechanism.
As a result, records do not meet federal vehicle safety standards for head restraints.
"If the vehicle is hit by the rear, the head restraint may not adequately protect passengers, thereby increasing the risk of injury," according to the statement posted on the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) site.
The recalled models were built between August 1 and September 10.
The deployment of GM pickups began in June and represents the largest vehicle launch for the first U.S. car manufacturer since its bankruptcy and restructuring in 2009.
GM informed pickup owners of the defect in the first fortnight of October.
NHTSA was unable to review the letter of information to owners due to the 16-day shutdown of government operations, which slowed down the growth in vehicle sales in October.
Sales of Silverado and Sierra pickups, which were redesigned for the 2014 model, increased by about 20% in the first 10 months of the year, said GM on Friday.
In October, GM sold 42,660 Silverado pickups and 16,503 Sierra pickups.
GM's stock price climbed 1.4% to $37.47 on the New York Stock Exchange Friday afternoon.
