The cry of despair of an Obama voter
I voted twice for President Obama, believing in the possibility of a change
He says Obama has made commendable efforts thwarted by the obstructionism of the Republican Party
Obstructionism does not excuse the difficulties of the Obamacare site, nor drone attacks
The memory of Obama's 2008 campaign is a sad reminder of what could have happened.
Nathaniel P. Morris is a 2nd year medical student at Harvard Faculty of Medicine.
I'm reading a awfully sad book these days.
It's a book that I thought would encourage me during the morosity of the second year of medicine and give me hope.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and it's the memories of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finished the medical reports of my patients in the evening and went to bed, this book takes me back to the time when politics inspired millions of people and where speeches could take your breath away.
The election ended with an overwhelming victory and newscasters took the time to reflect on the historic nature of the moment.
My comrades cried with joy and my parents kept all the newspapers they found.
A young team of visionaries was advancing towards the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During Obama's transition period before taking office in 2008, he had 82% favourable views.
And then I close the book.
The return to the present is a difficult awakening, it's like coming out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember these days full of optimism, they are like distant memories, a sad reminder of the opportunities of the past.
The change really happened in the years that followed the first time I voted.
It had nothing to do with what I had imagined.
I credit Obama with great achievements, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act to the departure of our army from Iraq, to the end of the "unseen and unknown" and the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that partisan obstructionism has destroyed too many efforts to advance our nation in the area of immigration reforms, public health care and the closure of Guantanamo, among other things.
But after repeatedly defending Obama's administration against my peers and colleagues, I can no longer provide explanations.
I am on the brink of political despair.
Republican obstruction cannot explain the wiretapping of foreign leaders, nor the attacks of innocent foreign children by drones.
She cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the privacy of Americans, nor the indictment of whistleblowers who reveal the government's misdeeds.
It cannot justify the murder of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without trial, nor the escape of public funding and the overexpenditure allowed during presidential campaigns.
It cannot justify the conclusions of a report which says that the White House's efforts to silence the media are "the most aggressive ... since the administration of Nixon".
And, more recently, she cannot excuse the impossibility of designing a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was ratified.
I don't know if that's what I expected.
If, at 18, I was supposed to understand that governance could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Of course, the electoral function is not predictable, because the opposition political party and the events that happen by chance, such as the Newton massacre, influence our public conversation.
However, all the examples I have listed above seem to be largely the choice of administration.
That's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unsophisticated alternative that did not seem to determine his policies or positions.
I felt that Obama, elected for a second term by being freed from the pressure of future elections, would keep the promises we had heard about for so long.
Yet, while the index of favorable opinions plunged below 45% this week, it is even more difficult to return to 2008 through this book.
He makes me want the many promises that have flown away.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Obama suffered huge losses to Clinton in Pennsylvania's Primary.
At a post-campaign meeting, he told his team that they had to get back on track and stay true to their cause.
"I want us to focus on our talent," he said.
We have to remember who we are.
We're five years later, Mr. President, and I don't agree with you anymore.
The views expressed in this commentary are only those of Nathaniel Morris.
