A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, scientific mission manager at the Observatoire pour la Conservation et l'Etude des Animaux et Milieus Marins (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
That is good news, but I am not particularly surprised.
While in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of species classification sciences.
Moreover, it is not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology call into question the classification or membership of a species in a genus, family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being questioned due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two closely related species were distinguished morphologically by genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have identified four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as the Wildlife Conservation Society has stated?
From a conservation perspective, knowledge of these genetic differences is essential to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
While this population had been known to researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only there.
Therefore, if there is a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than with a local disappearance of a population of a species that is more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered based on the number of existing individuals on Earth, that is, the stock, and the potential for recovery from neighbouring stocks.
As for the Sousa chinensis species, whose population of the new species was discovered, its stock automatically became smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which may eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It is important to know that the marine environment is the least well known.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Mariannes' pit, only 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
More money is spent on finding life on other planets than on marine research, and it is high time it changed.
RBS suspends two traders in the foreign exchange market
Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange market division according to two sources close to the file, again showing that the regulators' global investigation into suspicions of currency market manipulation is beginning to bear fruit.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, confirmed that they were cooperating with regulators in investigations into the world's largest financial market, where US$5.3 trillion is changing hands every day.
The two traders are the first RBS employees to be suspended as part of the expansion of the investigation that echoes the scandal of manipulations of the Libor interbank rate.
The bank, which refused to comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received requests for information from regulators.
"The ongoing investigation into this case is ongoing and we are fully cooperating with the CFA and other regulators," said a bank representative two weeks ago.
Last month, sources close to the file reported that RBS had sent emails and instant messages to and from a former trader to the British regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and was reportedly suspended from his position as European currency cash trader at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, European cash exchange trader at Citi, was on leave this week, while Matt Gardiner, senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been charged.
Mr. Usher's file included instant messages sent to and by bankers working at Barclays and Citigroup, adding sources close to the file.
UBS explained this week that it had brought an action against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator, Finma, stated that it was investigating suspicions of foreign exchange market manipulation in a number of Swiss banks.
Around the world, at least six authorities – the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are investigating allegations about bankers who have agreed to manipulate exchange rates.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Crédit Suisse also initiated internal investigations or received information requests from regulators, reported sources close to the file.
Banks scan instant messages and emails sent for years to find cases of wrongdoing.
The news about these investigations has shaken traders in a sector that has been one of the biggest growth engines of investment bank trading units in recent years, but has been questioned this year because of the low volatility of currencies that limits opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to minimize the case by saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the large highly liquid foreign exchange market, but senior traders explain that this is not necessarily true.
One senior trader said that despite the high volume of daily foreign exchange transactions, the fragmentation of liquidity between trading management platforms and the increasingly frequent use by banks of their own internal platforms "explains that it is possible to start having an impact on the market at little cost".
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced that it had sent a trader working in its London Stock Exchange fund office this week after it caused a $6 million loss at the end of last year.
The bank promptly informed the competent authorities and cooperated with the regulators.
"We are convinced that the trader acted alone and that the case has been mastered," said a representative of Credit Suisse.
