Supreme Court validates Obama's Health System Reform Act
Great victory for the Obama administration: the US Supreme Court today declared that the health system reform law ratified by Obama was constitutional.
By 5 votes to 4, the judges validated the individual mandate of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act – which requires citizens to take out health insurance by 2014, or to pay a fine – and declared that it was constitutional under the government's taxing power.
The President of the Supreme Court, John Roberts, joined the four most liberal members of the Court, while Justices Scalia, Thomas, Alito and Kennedy disagreed.
The Court also validated the other sections of the 2,700-page law and also considered that the provision of the Health System Reform Act, which stipulates that the eligibility threshold for Medicaid should be lowered under penalty of losing all federal funding for the programme, was coercive in accordance with the Constitution.
The procedure to block the law was initiated by 26 states and the National Federation of Independent Business.
All major Republican candidates in the 2012 presidential election, including candidate-designate Mitt Romney, were fiercely opposed to the law.
