Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents Dance Dance with her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by Henri Michaux's inks and poems, the second inspired by Satie's famous piano solos Gymnopédies.
An evening that allows to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and black ink to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, progresses, profile, fine as a line and clothed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple trait, takes its form.
And this form will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, entirely dressed in black, only the hands and face discovered, wait on either side of the playing area, rush when the next graphic appears, incarnate it, come out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in relay of solos, in group in unison (a mass that makes solo), in large group of twelve solos where each one executes his sign.
We think of "Glory of the morning", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, posed online at the forestage.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is strong, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the rhythm is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, part of Michaux' poem, monocord and monotonous in the scream, and will continue while dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to go back.
This loud and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a force at Chouinard - like those hairs that swirling or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has established herself, with her tics.
The result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a broader and gibbling imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches magic.
The audience liked it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnopedias, after the intermission, is richer.
The scene is partly draped with grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a neglected house.
On the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their clumsiness in music, touching, gives a real fragility.
On stage, spend couples, in romantic duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffoons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, with a red nose, in highly polarized male-female loving parades.
Loves are carnassiers, fugitives or players.
The gesture, the laughter and the little cries beautifully translate the archaic, the grace and the ridiculousness of the bodies into coitus, beings that melt.
But the play takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
There everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the dancers cabotinate, descend among the spectators, glare, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, spread the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness transpire, and it is Chouinard's art, there, to contaminate the public.
Google, Samsung and Huawei are being prosecuted for Nortel patents
The group that owns thousands of former Nortel patents began an avalanche of patent lawsuits on Thursday against mobile phone manufacturers, including Google, the company he put on the pole during the patent auction that took place after Nortel's bankruptcy.
Rockstar, the consortium that acquired Nortel patents for $4.5 billion, filed a complaint against Samsung Electronics Co Ltd, HTC Corp, Huawei and four other companies for patent infringement before the U.S. Assize Court in Texas.
Rockstar is jointly owned by Apple, Microsoft, Blackberry, Ericsson and Sony.
Google is accused of violating seven patents.
Patents contain technologies that make it possible to display advertising in relation to search terms on the Internet, indicated the findings of the trial, which is the core business of Google.
It was not possible to reach representatives of Samsung, Huawei, HTC and Rockstar.
Samsung, Huawei and HTC manufacture phones that operate under Google's Android operating system, which delivers fierce competition to Apple and Microsoft mobile products.
In 2011, Google made an initial offer of $900 million for Nortel's patents.
Google has increased its offer several times, finally offering $4.4 billion.
After losing Nortel patents to Rockstar, Google subsequently acquired Motorola Mobility for $12.5 billion, a market partly based on Motorola's patent library.
"Although Google failed in its attempt to acquire the patents at issue during the auction, it violated and continues to violate those patents," said the trial's findings.
Rockstar claims greater damages against Google because it claims that Google's patent infringement is obstinate, according to the complainant.
