Egypt asks the first freely elected president to take the oath
Mohamed Morsi took the oath of investiture, but it is unlikely that his day of triumph will mark the end of political conflicts in Egypt.
Islamist Mohamed Morsi promised the emergence of a "new Egypt" when he took the oath of investiture to the presidency, thus becoming the first freely elected president and succeeding Hosni Mubarak who was expelled from power 16 months earlier.
During his inauguration before the Constitutional High Court, Mr. Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and the fifth head of State of Egypt since the overthrow of the monarchy 60 years ago.
He was sworn in before the 18 judges in black robe of the Court whose building on the edge of the Nile was built to look like an Egyptian temple.
"We are looking for better tomorrows, a new Egypt and a second republic," said President Morsi during the solemn ceremony broadcast live on public television.
"Today, the Egyptian people have laid the foundations of a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy and stability," explained Mr. Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer formed in the United States, from the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group considered for more than 84 years since its formation as an illegal and harshly repressed organization by successive governments.
Hundreds of soldiers and police kept the building when Mr. Morsi arrived shortly after 11 a.m. local time, followed by a small convoy.
Only a few hundred supporters had gathered in front of the Court to acclaim the new president and, standing out from the presidential fascination of the Mubarak years, traffic was only briefly interrupted to allow his convoy to pass through the busy streets connecting the city centre with the southern suburbs.
Considered to be the uncharismatic "saving wheel" of the Muslim Brotherhood, his personal prestige has been considerably strengthened since his victory and his speech on Friday during which he tried to present himself as the candidate not only of the Islamists but of all those who want to finish the work begun during the 2011 uprising against the authoritarian President Mubarak.
