The press reports that the NSA has received millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some of the US allies, but the agency's director said this week that this was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the US.
Other revelations referred to documents disclosed by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other Heads of State.
The Director of Intelligence, James Clapper, justified the Allied espionage by stating that it was necessary and common practice on both sides.
In this tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a congressional trip, scheduled to take place this year, and that he hoped that the delegation would include members of both parties and of both chambers.
